<Layout
  title="Resources | Accessibility Research Lab | Western Washington University">

  <!-- main element starts here
    -->
	<div class="page-content">
		<div class="region-wrapper">
			<h1 class="page-title">Resources</h1>
			<div class="layout layout--onecol ">
				<div class="layout__region">
					<h2>Accessibility Resources at Western</h2>
					<h3>Some Basic Guides</h3>
					<ul>
						<li><a href="https://urm.wwu.edu/accessibility/documents">Creating Accessible Documents</a></li>
						<li><a href="https://urm.wwu.edu/email#a11y">Writing Accessible Emails</a></li>
						<li><a href="https://urm.wwu.edu/accessibility/social-media">Creating Accessible Social Media Content</a></li>
						<li><a href="https://urm.wwu.edu/accessibility/guide">Searchable Web Accessibility Guide</a></li>
					</ul>
					<h3>Canvas Trainings</h3>
					<ul>
						<li><a href="https://urm.wwu.edu/accessibility/standard-training">Standard Accessibility Training</a>
							introduces the basics of creating accessible web content and other types of digital documents.
						</li>
						<li>
							<a href="https://urm.wwu.edu/accessibility/advanced-training">Advanced Accessibility Training</a>
							covers topics like the Document Object Model, HTML/CSS, JavaScript, and Accessible Rich Internet Applications.
						</li>
					</ul>
					<h3>Silktide</h3>
					<p>
						Western offers access to <a href="https://login.silktide.com">Silktide</a>, a tool that will help evaluate your webpages automatically for web governance issues such as; accessibility, quality assurance like spelling and grammar, search engine optimization, and more, plus it has a deep  toolset to analyze the data you receive from them.
					</p>
					<h2>More Questions?</h2>
					<p>You can also contact Western's resident experts for help:</p>
					<ul>
						<li><a href="https://www.wwu.edu/gerardc">Carly Gerard</a>
							, Web Accessibility Engineer
						</li>
						<li><a href="https://www.wwu.edu/engebrd2">David Engebretson</a>
							, Digital Technologies Accessibility Coordinator
						</li>
					</ul>

					
					 
					<h2>World Wide Web Consortium (w3) Information
					</h2>
					<p>The <a href="https://www.w3.org/">World Wide Web Consortium (W3C)</a> maintains international standards for web development. These standards include issues regarding accessibility for all people.
						
						<!--- -->
						<a href="https://www.w3.org/">WCAG (Web Content Accessibility Guidelines)</a>, a set of standards specifically to ensure web content is accessible.</p>
					<p>W3C also offers a fantastic set of resources on creating accessible web content as part of its <a href="https://www.w3.org/WAI/">Web Accessibility Initiative</a>. This includes resources for:</p>
					<ul>
						<li><a href="https://www.w3.org/WAI/roles/writers/">Content Writers</a></li>
						<li><a href="https://www.w3.org/WAI/roles/designers/">Designers</a></li>
						<li><a href="https://www.w3.org/WAI/roles/developers/">Developers</a></li>
						<li><a href="https://www.w3.org/WAI/roles/trainers/">Trainers and Educators</a></li>
					</ul>
					<h3>WebAIM</h3>
					<p>The nonprofit <a href="https://www.webaim.org">WebAIM</a> also has useful checklists, cheat sheets, and tools for making digital content accessible.</p>
					<h2>Accessibility Beyond the Web</h2>
					<p>The <a href="https://www.ahead.org">Association on Higher Education and Disability (AHEAD)</a> is a professional membership association that centers on making higher education accessible.</p>
					<p><a href="https://teachaccess.org/">Teach Access</a> is a nonprofit working to close the accessible technology skills gap at universities and corporations.</p>
					<p><a href="https://www.ada.gov/">ADA.gov</a> contains a wealth of resources on what makes digital and physical spaces accessible. Plus, they define the rules.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
				
			
		</div> <!-- end region-wrapper -->

	</div> <!-- end page-content -->

</layout>